<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: TEAM PLAYER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Pat H. Broeske 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Sly Stallone has a prison pic, "Lock-Up," due in August from Tri-Star. But he's 
not exactly Rambo-ish about taking on the summer competition. "Have you ever 
seen so much hype? Definitely scary," Sly admits. "I figure I should stay low 
profile. I'm purposely not going to be doing any sky writing." 
</P>
<P>
The $24-million film, directed by John Flynn ("Best Seller") and shot largely 
at New Jersey's Rahway State Prison, is now being rushed through 
postproduction. ("We cut the film in just 12 days.") He calls it "the closest 
thing I've done to 'Rocky,' in that it's really an ensemble piece. My character 
is reliant on a lot of other people -- a support system." Pat H. Broeske 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061889-0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 71604 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 18, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 20; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
127 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUTTAKES: TEAM PLAYER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Pat H. Broeske 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Meanwhile, he's at work on the tentatively titled "Set-Up," which just began 
filming for Warners. The Guber-Peters production, with Andre Konchalovsky 
directing, co-stars Sly and Kurt Russell as two cops who are set up and 
imprisoned, then break out and go after the villains. "But this isn't a prison 
movie like 'Lock-Up.' The prison scenes take up only about four pages (of the 
script)." 
</P>
<P>
 He insists the back-to-back pics are not a comeback: "Oh, c'mon! 'Rambo III' 
may have gotten scathing reviews, but it came in 11th at the (1988) box office 
(gross: $53 million). And it did some good foreign box office. This is just 
another cycle of my career. 
</P>
<P>
"I'm returning to a safer place -- doing some interacting, after playing it 
solo." Pat H. Broeske 
