<HEADLINE>
<P>
FEWER YOUNG COUPLES CAN BUY HOMES, STUDY FINDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's getting tougher for young couples to buy a home. According to a recent 
study, between 1975 and 1985 the Census Bureau reports that less than half of 
the married couples between the ages of 25 and 34 had incomes high enough to by 
their first home. 
</P>
<P>
In the mid-70's, three-fourths of such couples could afford starter homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA061889-0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 71884 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 18, 1989, Sunday, Home Edition 
