<HEADLINE>
<P>
HARVARD CREW FINISHES FIRST; UCLA IS LAST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By AP 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BANTAM, Ohio 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Harvard won its third consecutive national collegiate rowing championship 
Saturday with a two-second victory over Washington. 
</P>
<P>
The Harvard crew covered the 2,000-meter course on Lake Harsha in 5 minutes 
35.5 seconds to win the Herschede Cup, symbolizing the national championship. 
Washington, which won the 1984 title, finished in 5:38.93. The Huskies, lost 
the Pacific Coast rowing championship to UCLA this season. 
</P>
<P>
Northeastern, which beat Harvard in a dual regatta earlier this year, was third 
in 5:39.61. Pennsylvania, the Intercollegiate Rowing Assn. champion, was fourth 
in 5:39.81; Wisconsin, which won the national championship in 1986, was fifth 
in 5:42.47, and UCLA was last in 5:43.35. 
</P>
<P>
The race was held at East Fork State Park, east of Cincinnati. As the champion, 
Harvard gained a berth in the Henley Royal Regatta in England. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Game Story; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ROWING; HARVARD UNIVERSITY; COLLEGE ATHLETICS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
